    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If your Monstera's roots are rotting, it's important to act quickly to save the plant. Start by removing it from the pot and gently washing off the old soil. Look for any mushy or blackened roots, which indicate rot. Trim away the affected roots with sterilized scissors or pruning shears. Allow the plant to dry for a day or two before repotting it in fresh, well-draining potting mix. You might also want to consider adding a fungicide to the soil to help prevent further fungal issues. Once repotted, make sure to water it sparingly, allowing the soil to dry out slightly between waterings. Keep an eye on the plant, and it should start to recover as long as you take good care of it going forward.",
      "source": "target",
