    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The spreading brown spots and the crunchy texture you're describing might indeed be a fungal infection, such as anthracnose or a leaf spot disease, which are common in Monstera deliciosa. To differentiate between a simple fungus and a more serious issue, observe the pattern and color change of the spots. Fungal spots often have a darker border and may ooze a spore-like substance. If the spots are spreading rapidly and causing the leaves to wither, it could be a more aggressive fungus or a secondary infection. To combat this, you can apply a fungicide specifically designed for foliage plants. Be sure to follow the instructions for application, and you may also want to increase air circulation around your plant by spacing it out or occasionally rotating it. With proper care, your Monstera should start to bounce back. If you notice any signs of pests, such as tiny insects or webbing, you might need to treat for those as well. Keep a close eye on your plant, and don't hesitate to reach out to a local nursery or plant expert if you're unsure.",
